Taken at Ebara Shrine.

Ebara Shrine is located on the old Tōkaidō Road in Shinagawa, Tokyo. It was supposedly founded under the patronage of Minamoto Yoritomo, the first Kamakura shogun. 


The young Emperor Meiji visited here on his journey from Kyoto to Edo after the fall of the Tokugawa shogunate.

photo.title: About to make a wish

description._content:
I had to wait a few minutes but eventually got a clear shot of these girls about to tie on a wish.

On our first day in Kyoto, we walked up to Kiyomizudera Temple which was near to where we were staying. It was a Sunday afternoon at the end of the autumn leaves season. I was surprised at how many Japanese - male and female though mostly female - were wearing traditional clothes. We saw more here than anywhere else. I wondered if it was because it was a Sunday and also the last of the autumn colours season. There were lots of selfies being taken :-)

photo.title: Hakone Shrine Mural

description._content: Looks like Mt. Fuji above the shrine and the famous peace Torii below it in Ashi Lake. I don't know the significance of the horse. Later: The original shrine is at the nearby peak of Mt. Komagatake (positioned at what is said to be the back of Hakone Shrine as a sacred place). The rock wrapped in rope in front of the original shrine is called “Bakouseki”, and it’s said to be the rock on which a god descended upon a white horse. photo.title: Boeing E-767 74-3503 JASDF taxiing at Hyakuri AB

description._content: Boeing E-767 74-3503 (cn 28016/618), Japan Air Self-Defense Force (JASDF), Keikai Kokutai (Airborne Early Warning Wing), 602 Hikotai (Squadron) based at Hamamatsu pictured at Hyakuri AB (photo 6933-2). The Boeing E-767 is an Airborne Warning and Control System (AWACS) aircraft. It was designed in response to the Japan Air Self-Defense Force's requirements, and is essentially the Boeing E-3 Sentry's surveillance radar and air control system installed on a Boeing 767-200. The first E-767 made the first flight on October 4, 1994 at Paine Field, Washington. First flight with the rotodome installed occurred on August 9, 1996 and it was delivered to JASDF on March 11, 1998 along with the second E-767. Aircraft No. 3 and No. 4 were delivered on January 5, 1999. On May 10, 2000, all four E-767s were put into service with Airborne Early Warning Group (AEWG) 601st Squadron at JASDF Hamamatsu Air Base. (The airbase's runways needed to be reinforced to accommodate the E-767.) On March 31, 2005, the two squadrons were merged. The electronics system on the E-767 is essentially the same as the later E-3 models, using Northrop Grumman's (formerly Westinghouse Electronic Systems) AN/APY-2 Passive electronically scanned array radar system. In November 2006, Boeing was awarded a contract to deliver Radar System Improvement Program (RSIP) kits to Japan's fleet of four E-767 Airborne Warning and Control System (AWACS) aircraft. RSIP increases (among other things) the AWACS aircraft's radar sensitivity, allowing it to detect and track smaller targets. It also improves the radar's existing computer with a new high-reliability multi-processor and rewrites the software to facilitate future maintenance and enhancements. Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_E-767

photo.title: Come get it!

description._content: The Force Awakens had a lot of "whoa" moments for me, but this one was silent. Finn's bravery sent a tremor down my spine. Finn looked terrified; like he had no idea what he was doing. All he knew was that he was defending his friend. He also knew he was probably gonna die doing so. This was his defining moment. Finn had reached the end of his character arc in this story. He started out as a villain and ended a true hero. Where will Finn's character go from here? If you're interested, I posted a photo of how I took this shot here. And if you're also interested, here is a before/after editing comparison shot.

photo.title: About to make a wish

description._content:
I had to wait a few minutes but eventually got a clear shot of these girls about to tie on a wish.

On our first day in Kyoto, we walked up to Kiyomizudera Temple which was near to where we were staying. It was a Sunday afternoon at the end of the autumn leaves season. I was surprised at how many Japanese - male and female though mostly female - were wearing traditional clothes. We saw more here than anywhere else. I wondered if it was because it was a Sunday and also the last of the autumn colours season. There were lots of selfies being taken :-)

photo.title: Hakone Shrine Mural

description._content: Looks like Mt. Fuji above the shrine and the famous peace Torii below it in Ashi Lake. I don't know the significance of the horse. Later: The original shrine is at the nearby peak of Mt. Komagatake (positioned at what is said to be the back of Hakone Shrine as a sacred place). The rock wrapped in rope in front of the original shrine is called “Bakouseki”, and it’s said to be the rock on which a god descended upon a white horse. Source: planetyze.com/en/japan/hakone/hakone-shrine

photo.title: Boeing E-767 74-3503 JASDF taxiing at Hyakuri AB

description._content: Boeing E-767 74-3503 (cn 28016/618), Japan Air Self-Defense Force (JASDF), Keikai Kokutai (Airborne Early Warning Wing), 602 Hikotai (Squadron) based at Hamamatsu pictured at Hyakuri AB (photo 6933-2). The Boeing E-767 is an Airborne Warning and Control System (AWACS) aircraft. It was designed in response to the Japan Air Self-Defense Force's requirements, and is essentially the Boeing E-3 Sentry's surveillance radar and air control system installed on a Boeing 767-200. The first E-767 made the first flight on October 4, 1994 at Paine Field, Washington. First flight with the rotodome installed occurred on August 9, 1996 and it was delivered to JASDF on March 11, 1998 along with the second E-767. Aircraft No. 3 and No. 4 were delivered on January 5, 1999. On May 10, 2000, all four E-767s were put into service with Airborne Early Warning Group (AEWG) 601st Squadron at JASDF Hamamatsu Air Base. (The airbase's runways needed to be reinforced to accommodate the E-767.) On March 31, 2005, the two squadrons were merged. The electronics system on the E-767 is essentially the same as the later E-3 models, using Northrop Grumman's (formerly Westinghouse Electronic Systems) AN/APY-2 Passive electronically scanned array radar system. In November 2006, Boeing was awarded a contract to deliver Radar System Improvement Program (RSIP) kits to Japan's fleet of four E-767 Airborne Warning and Control System (AWACS) aircraft. RSIP increases (among other things) the AWACS aircraft's radar sensitivity, allowing it to detect and track smaller targets. It also improves the radar's existing computer with a new high-reliability multi-processor and rewrites the software to facilitate future maintenance and enhancements. Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_E-767

photo.title: Come get it!

description._content: The Force Awakens had a lot of "whoa" moments for me, but this one was silent. Finn's bravery sent a tremor down my spine. Finn looked terrified; like he had no idea what he was doing. All he knew was that he was defending his friend. He also knew he was probably gonna die doing so. This was his defining moment. Finn had reached the end of his character arc in this story. He started out as a villain and ended a true hero. Where will Finn's character go from here? If you're interested, I posted a photo of how I took this shot here. And if you're also interested, here is a before/after editing comparison shot.

description._content: Taken thirty seconds after “Yasukuni-dori and JR Bridges across It in 2015 April: 2.” In the previous photo, red and blue cranes and a white truck were shown. In this photo, the red crane had gone and the blue crane had moved toward the left edge of the photo (toward Akihabara Station). It was one hour after Yamanote and Keihin-tohoku re-started the service. It seems that they finally confirmed that the broken power line pylon was fixed and was leaving the site.

photo.title: Until I saw you. (Fuji Mountain in Japan)

description._content:
The cloud on the left looks like? 

My original plan was to take the mirror image of Fuji Mt. through The Lake Kawaguchi (河口湖); however, it was cloudy and misty in the morning.  After visiting the lake by taking the cruising ship, En Soleil, I took the Kachikachi Ropeway (天上公園纜車) to Tenjoyama Park Mt. to luckily capture this brief moment. It was really an awesome trip to Japan and I cannot wait to visit Tokyo again in the future.
